-1&3\\
\end{pmatrix} = 
</math>
:<math>
\begin{pmatrix}
3&64\\
1&32\\
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
1&-2\\
-1&3\\
\end{pmatrix} = 
</math>
:<math>
\begin{pmatrix}
-61&186\\
-31&94\\
\end{pmatrix}
</math>
We see that P and it's inverse disappear when you raise the matrix to the fifth power. Thus you can see that we can calculate A<sup>n</sup> very easily because you only have to raise the diagonal matrix to the n-th power. Raising diagonal matrices to a certain power is very easy because you only have to raise the numbers on the diagonal to that power.

